in Ireland and in Scotland, where the family's medieval ancestral seat is sited on the Ayrshire coast, facing the Irish Sea. — The great-grandparents of President John Fitzgerald Kennedy (1917–63) came to North America as immigrants from Ireland in the 1840s. His paternal great-grandparents were Patrick Kennedy (1823–58), born in Dunganstown, County Wexford, Ireland, and Bridget Murphy, who was born probably in Owenduff, County Wexford, Ireland <i>c.</i> 1827; they came to Boston, MA, in 1849. His maternal great-grandparents were Thomas Fitzgerald (1823–85), who was born in Bruff, County Limerick, Ireland, and Rose Anna Cox, who was born probably in Tomregan or Kinawley, County Cavan, Ireland, <i>c.</i> 1835; they came to Boston, MA, in 1857. — An early Scottish Kennedy forebear of a quite different family was British colonial official Archibald Kennedy (1685–1763), the son of Alexander Kennedy of Craigoch, who emigrated to NY <i>c.</i> 1710."],"variants":[{"name":"Canada","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canaday   and   Canida  .","Spanish (<b>Cañada</b>): topographic name from <i>cañada</i> ‘glen, valley’."]},{"name":"Cannady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canady  ,   Cannaday  , and   Kannady  ."]},{"name":"Cannaday","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canaday  ."]},{"name":"Canedy","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Cannedy  ."]},{"name":"Cannedy","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canedy  ."]},{"name":"Canaday","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canada   and   Cannaday  ."]},{"name":"Canady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canada  ,   Canaday  , and   Kanady  ."]},{"name":"Canida","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  ."]},{"name":"Kanady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Canady  ."]},{"name":"Kannady","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and Scottish   Kennedy  . Compare   Cannady   and   Kanady  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert Kennedy was born in 1290, in Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Gilbert Fitz Roland, was 37 and his mother, Mary De Carrick, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Lady Agnes Maxwell of Pollok. He died in 1385, in Scotland, at the age of 95."},"et":{"1290–1385":"1290–1385","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1253–1306":"1253–1306","1259–1310":"1259–1310","1259":"1259","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1253":"1253","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Renfrewshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland","Dunure Castle, Carrick, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carrick, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1290–1385":"1290–1385","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1253–1306":"1253–1306","1259–1310":"1259–1310","1259":"1259","1345":"1345","1310":"1310","1385":"1385","1253":"1253","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Renfrewshire, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Dunure, Ayrshire, Scotland","Dunure